<subSubSection pageId="22" pageNumber="223" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="22.[151,1437,582,825]" pageId="22" pageNumber="223">
This stalked species has umbilicate and yellow sporocarps. The slender stalk is not furrowed and is 
<quantity box="[1335,1437,618,645]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="9.3" pageId="22" pageNumber="223" unit="mm" value="0.93">0.93 mm</quantity>
long, black at the base then orange-yellow to orange-red at the top. The peridium is yellow with white lime. Opened specimens show orange-red at the base and bright yellow nodes stretched from the stalk to the peridium. Under the microscope, the spores are 8– 9 μm, smooth, clear. The capillitium consists of yellow granular nodes 225 μm long x 9 μm thick, stretched from stalk to peridium. Hypothallus black. Altogether, these features distinguish this specimen from all known species of 
<taxonomicName box="[449,564,798,824]" class="Myxomycetes" family="Physaraceae" genus="Badhamia" kingdom="Fungi" order="Physarales" pageId="22" pageNumber="223" phylum="Mycetozoa" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[449,564,798,824]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="223">Badhamia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
or 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Persoon" authorityYear="1794" box="[601,715,798,824]" class="Myxomycetes" family="Physaraceae" genus="Physarum" kingdom="Fungi" order="Physarales" pageId="22" pageNumber="223" phylum="Mycetozoa" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[601,715,798,824]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="223">Physarum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
